  <\remark>
    A scalar field <math|f> does not depends on a coordinate system. Given a coordinate system <math|<around*|{|x<rsup|\<mu\>>|}>>, the scalar field <math|f> can be represented by\ 

    <\equation*>
      F<around*|(|x<rsup|1>,\<ldots\>,x<rsup|n>|)>.
    </equation*>

    In this monograph, we do not distinguish

    <\equation*>
      <frac|\<partial\>F<around*|(|x|)>|\<partial\>x<rsup|\<mu\>>><space|1em><text|v.s.><space|1em><frac|\<partial\>f<around*|(|x|)>|\<partial\>x<rsup|\<mu\>>>
    </equation*>

    when the coordinate system is well-defined in the context.
  </remark>

  <\definition>
    A <with|font-shape|italic|vector> in <math|p\<in\>\<cal-M\>> is defined as a mapping in

    <\equation*>
      \<cal-F\><rsub|\<cal-M\>>\<rightarrow\>\<bbb-R\>,
    </equation*>

    where <math|\<cal-F\><rsub|\<cal-M\>>> is a scalar field in <math|p>.
  </definition>

  <\example>
    Define <math|x<rsub|\<mu\>>:\<cal-F\><rsub|\<cal-M\>>\<rightarrow\>\<bbb-R\>> such that

    <\equation*>
      x<rsub|\<mu\>><around*|(|f|)>\<triangleq\><around*|\<nobracket\>|<frac|\<partial\>F<around*|(|x|)>|\<partial\>x<rsup|\<mu\>>>|\|><rsub|p>,
    </equation*>

    where <math|F> is a coordinate system in <math|p>.
  </example>

  <\claim>
    If <math|p\<in\>\<cal-M\>> has two coordinate system with corresponding two set of basis vectors <math|<around*|{|x<rsub|\<mu\>>|}>> and <math|<around*|{|x<rprime|'><rsub|\<nu\>>|}>>, i.e., any vector <math|v> in <math|p> that can be represented by

    <\equation*>
      v=v<rsup|\<mu\>>x<rsub|\<mu\>>=v<rprime|'><rsup|\<nu\>>x<rprime|'><rsub|\<nu\>>
    </equation*>

    satisfies

    <\equation>
      v<rprime|'><rsup|\<nu\>>=<around*|\<nobracket\>|<frac|\<partial\>x<rsup|\<nu\>>|\<partial\>x<rsup|\<mu\>>>|\|><rsub|p>v<rsup|\<mu\>>.<label|eq:change-of-coordinates>
    </equation>
  </claim>

